<Author>berkshire_nomads
<Content>Why all the fuss ? At the time of writing, Tripadvisor rates this as one of the top 50 hotels in Paris, out of well over 1 000. Not sure I can see why. There's nothing wrong with it, but nothing that great either. The rooms are pretty small (mine certainly was). It's impossible to get a decent shower because it's underpowered and mounted at an odd angle. The location is not ideal - you have to walk 10 mins to get anywhere - not just the sights, but even a decent cafe or restaurant. The Arc de Triomphe, from which it takes its name, is a good 15 mins brisk walk. It's also very geared to the mass tourist market - each morning there were tour company desks set out in the lobby, and regularly large crowds milling around waiting to be herded off somewhere. I had a business meeting one morning and the only place we could get coffee was to join the throng in the restaurant for breakfast - noisy, crowded and slow service. The building is well kept and the decor is fairly funky but fails to endow the hotel with any real atmosphere. I think this must be the reason for the high rating. Many of the reviews are from non - Europeans and apart from the decor you could be anywhere; nicely insulated from the eccentricities of Paris. The week before I stayed in the Hotel du Louvre, which attracts more critical reviews because its older and to an extent showing its age. Nonetheless, it was in a better location, 鈧?50 less per night, and staying there you really feel like you are in Paris. I know where I'll be booking next trip. 
