<Content>Beautiful decor but expensive We stayed at the Hilton Arc d'Triomphe for 5 days at the end of May occupying 2 rooms. My husband and I had a garden view room (using reward points for part of the stay) and my daughter and mother-in-law had a street facing room. Neither rooms were noisy, both were large and beautifuly decorated. At check-in we were informed that the Executive level was full, a disappointment as we were gold level members. As compensatioln, we were given passes to breakfast for each day of our stay but no access to the executive lounge.A big disappointment was the quality of the bed. We booked into Hilton partially because we thought we knew quality of Hilton beds. Not the same here as in the U.S.--hard as a rock. I was having severe muscle spasms in my back by the third night. The very first thing my daughter noticed was how hard her bed was and we all were sore from the beds.Another unwelcome surprise was that the pool/fitness facilities were extra--25 Euros (a little over $30) to use the hot tub per person per usage. We have been overseas before but had really not encountered that before (maybe just didn't notice it).Internet was also very expensive to use. We ate at the hotel and ordered room service and it was great food (expensive but we expected that).The staff was very nice but there were just a few problems. Our toilet ran constantly. They sent someone to work on it the first day but the answer was that we had to jiggle the button until it stopped. That got old. Housekeeping never did figure it out and every day when we returned it was running and we had to go work with it. (Room was 320E per night or a little over $400!)Remote control for television did not work in my daughter's room but she called and they took care of that within the hour. When our reward nights were over and we began paying for the rest of the nights, we had to go through check-out/check-in with room keys. (A bit of a hassle after a long day of touring.)It was a beautiful hotel but for the money, I would stay somewhere with beds more comfortable and a bit closer to the Louvre/Orsay areas. 
