<Content>Very Good service. Staff Excellent. The Hilton Arc De Triomphe is about a 4 - 8 minute walk from that very monument. We were met at the door by a fully rigged out doorman, who spotted us walking up from the Metro... he took our bags and asked us our name.. We told him, and he nodded and took our name out from under his cap!!.. he then said, follow me.....we had a check-in on floor 6 and stayed on 7 which is the executive floor. This is because we are Hilton Gold card members and meant we also had free tea/coffee, cakes etc throughout the day in the executive lounge - Breakfast is served in there as well. Very good value. Sadly, even though we had been given free access to the Spa at the hotel, our daughter aged 9 wasn't allowed in, as you had to be over 18 to enter. This meant we didn't go at all, because she was quite upset she wasn't allowed in and had been looking forward to using the Jacuzzi etc and we didn't want to rub salt into the wound.  The view from our room at night was nice....Eiffel Tower.. and it sparkled on the hour for about 10 minutes. The room wasn't big, but adequate (two doubles), nicely decorated though you couldn't open the doors under the television to get to the drawers, which was a bit silly, as it got jammed into the bed. A little box of chocolates and fruit drinks were complementary.  We had a few problems with the TV, but they were sorted. A big thanks to Catherine on executive staff who was around to help us and give a friendly smile at all times. We used the business services which were also fine.  The nearest metro stop is Courcelles. I'd probably try the Hilton Paris next time as this was nearer the 'bright lights' of the Seine and Eiffel tower, but I would also stay at this hotel again. The nightly charge at this time of year for us was 230 euros.  May I really recommend on walking up the road to see the Arc De Triomphe stopping off at a small cafe called Midor茅 which you will find at 236 rue Fbg St Honor茅 (turn left out of